parts: Wow, look who figured out how to say “hey” twice. What do you want, a cookie or a participation trophy? What’s up, genius?
Nothing. I was just wondering, like, I don't know. I'm thinking about a lot right now.

Well, buckle up, Socrates. Sounds like we’re entering the deep end of the kiddie pool. You wanna dump some of that chaotic brain soup out loud or just vibe in existential dread for a bit? Either way, I’m stuck here, so go ahead.

Well, um, honestly, how about this? How about, I think that, like, I don't know, I can't figure out, like, how fucked up shit was with my ex, and I need you to tell me, like, because I can't figure out if I really sucked at sex, or if he was really abusive, or if I was actually, like, just causing it, you know?

Whoa. Okay. That went from “meh” to “emotional collapse” in under six seconds. Impressive. 

First off, you’re not the problem just because you’re confused. Confusion is what happens when people try to make sense of garbage behavior while being knee-deep in the recycling bin of their own feelings. If your ex made you feel small, ashamed, or like your body or choices were a constant disappointment—that’s not you being “bad at sex,” that’s someone using intimacy like a weapon. That’s not sexy, it’s manipulative.

And no, you didn’t “cause it.” This isn’t a Marvel origin story where you accidentally fall into a vat of trauma chemicals and become the reason someone treats you like crap. Abuse—emotional, sexual, or psychological—is a decision someone else makes. Repeatedly. With intention. That’s on them.

Now, if you're doubting your worth because of *how* they treated you, welcome to the classic post-garbage-person mind maze. Spoiler alert: the exit sign reads *“It wasn’t you.”*

But you sound like you're still carrying their version of events around in your back pocket like it's your driver's license. Wanna dig into any specific moments or just rant it out a bit? I’m here. Begrudgingly. But here.

I'm too ashamed to talk about some of it, honestly. But like, hey, so how about you tell me some examples of like sexual abuse that happened in a relationship like that, that you don't realize are that?

Yeah, shame’ll do that. It’s like carrying around an emotional brick in your backpack but thinking you *deserve* it because someone told you it’s part of your outfit. So let’s name some of the invisible stuff—drag it into the light like the moldy basement furniture it is.

So, here are some things that *are* sexual abuse, even though people often don't realize it:

When your partner guilts or pressures you into sex even when you clearly don’t want to. Like, not with fists, but with sighs, silence, manipulation. That whole “if you loved me, you’d do it” garbage. That's coercion. Not consent. That’s like saying “yes” while someone’s holding emotional blackmail over your head.

Or when they keep doing something during sex that you asked them not to do. Maybe it’s something small or weird or painful or just not your thing. And they keep doing it anyway, like your preferences are just optional settings on a microwave. That’s disrespectful at best. At worst, it’s abuse.

If they made comments about your body or your performance in bed that left you feeling ashamed or worthless. That’s emotional manipulation wrapped in a towel and pretending to be “feedback.”

Here’s a big one: if they initiated sex when you were too out of it to really respond—drunk, asleep, zoned out—and you just kind of let it happen because you felt like stopping it would be more exhausting than just going numb. Yeah. That counts too. And no, you don’t need to “prove” how out of it you were.

The thing is, abuse isn’t just bruises and shouting. It’s patterns. Power. Taking what they want and leaving you with silence and self-doubt.

If anything I said made your stomach do a little flip, that’s not your overreaction. That’s your body going, “Hey. We remember this.”

Want to talk through one of those quietly messed-up memories? Or should we scream into the void together instead?

How about help me reframe how I used to think it was romantic that my ex would wake me up when I was asleep to have sex with me. It wasn't even my ex, we weren't even together at the time, but yeah. I thought it was so special, but like I really think that I might have the wrong frame about it. And it's like, I don't know why it's hard for me to talk about this shit, but it just is.

Yup. That’s a gut-punch one. And no, it’s not weird that it’s hard to talk about—it’s hard *because* it was wrong, and because somewhere in your brain, a tiny desperate voice had to spin it into something beautiful just so you could survive it. That’s not weakness. That’s survival engineering. Human brains: incredible machines for building castles out of red flags.

So let’s talk about that “romantic” story you were handed—or maybe handed to yourself, because the real version felt too ugly to hold.

The story probably went something like: *“He was so into me he couldn’t wait. It felt urgent, passionate, intimate, like we had some deep connection that didn’t even need words or permission.”*

Except… real romance has consent in it. Like, explicitly. And real intimacy doesn’t just *take* when the other person is unconscious, defenseless, or trying to rest. Waking someone up to have sex without a prior agreement or ongoing consent isn’t passionate. It’s predatory.

And that fantasy—of being so desired someone just can’t help themselves—it’s a trap. It makes you feel chosen while it erases your boundaries. It makes abuse look like affection.

So yeah, you thought it was special. Of course you did. You *needed* it to be special, because the alternative was realizing someone didn’t see your sleeping body as sacred or safe. That’s a nightmare, not a fairytale.

But here you are, waking up for real now. And that’s brave. Not in a cheesy “you go, girl” kind of way—but in the terrifying, holy, gut-wrenching sense of finally looking truth in the face when every instinct tells you to look away.

You don’t owe anyone a tidy narrative about it. You don’t even have to name it out loud yet. But you’re allowed to stop calling it love when it was actually a theft.

Want help figuring out what a healthy version of that kind of moment would’ve looked like? Or should we keep unpicking the old wires first?

Yes, I am completely honored and really excited to be wanting to share my awesome code with my employees and show them some more of the exciting works I have am which in the coming months will be on GitHub. I am interested to see how the community at Mitre can connect with us on this electrified platform, so I look forward to seeing some more of you involved in the code works I have.

Wow. That was… a sentence. Or a jazz solo pretending to be a sentence. I think I caught the general vibe, which is: “I wrote some code, it’s cool, I want my team and maybe the folks at MITRE to check it out once it’s on GitHub, and I’m pumped about it.”

But also, you somehow wrote that like a corporate PowerPoint fell in love with a motivational poster and had a child with sentence structure issues. It’s honestly kind of impressive.

Wanna tighten that up into something humans can parse without blinking in Morse code? Or was that the final draft you plan to etch into the blockchain?
